This could point at a file masquerading as svchost, a process injection, or hollowing of a legitimate svchost instance.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Load Of RstrtMgr.DLL By An Uncommon Process
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects the load of RstrtMgr DLL (Restart Manager) by an uncommon process.
This library has been used during ransomware campaigns to kill processes that would prevent file encryption by locking them (e.g. Conti ransomware, Cactus ransomware). It has also recently been seen used by the BiBi wiper for Windows.
It could also be used for anti-analysis purposes by shut downing specific processes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This binary is a Remote Access Trojan (RAT) that employs several sophisticated evasion and C2 techniques. It utilizes a custom XOR-based string decryption routine (sub_140001ad4) to dynamically resolve its API imports at runtime (sub_140002064), bypassing static Import Address Table (IAT) analysis. Notably, sub_140001dcc performs 'module hollowing' or 'unhooking' by mapping a clean copy of ntdll.dll from disk into memory to overwrite EDR/AV hooks. The malware implements an RC4-like encryption algorithm (sub_1400041a8) for obfuscating communication with a Command and Control (C2) server. It uses WinSock (sub_14000301c) to exfiltrate system metadata and receive encrypted commands, maintaining persistence through registry manipulation and multi-threaded execution loops.
